Bring a large #pot of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Peel and mince @garlic{1%clove}. Trim ends from @zucchini{1}. Using a #peeler, shave zucchini lengthwise into thin ribbons, rotating as you go, until you get to the seedy core; discard core.

> Swap in chicken sausage or ground beef for pork sausage.

Once water is boiling, add @spaghetti{6%ounce} to #pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}.

Reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water (1 cup for 4 servings), then drain.

While pasta cooks, remove sausage from casing if necessary; discard casing. Heat @olive oil{1%teaspoon} in a large #pan over medium-high heat. Add @ground beef{10%ounce} and cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in garlic and @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tablespoon}; cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Add @marinara cup{14%ounce} to #pan with sausage mixture, then reduce heat to medium. Simmer until flavors meld and sauce has slightly reduced, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add drained spaghetti, ¼ cup reserved pasta cooking water (½ cup for 4 servings), and @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4) to #pan with sauce. Toss to thoroughly combine.

Separate zucchini ribbons with your hands, then stir into pasta until slightly softened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. TIP: If needed, stir in more reserved pasta cooking water a splash at a time until spaghetti is thoroughly coated in sauce.

Divide pasta between bowls; top with @parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon} and serve.

> Ground Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.